</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Sudden cardiac death is defined as death from unexpected circulatory arrest—usually a result of cardiac arrhythmia—that occurs within 1 hour of the onset of symptoms. Proper and timely identification of individuals at risk for sudden cardiac death and the diagnosis of its predisposing conditions are vital. A careful history and physical examination, in addition to electrocardiography and cardiac imaging, are essential to identify conditions associated with sudden cardiac death. Among young adults (18–35 years), sudden cardiac death most commonly results from a previously undiagnosed congenital or hereditary condition, such as coronary artery anomalies and inherited cardiomyopathies (eg, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy [ARVC], dilated cardiomyopathy, and noncompaction cardiomyopathy). Overall, the most common causes of sudden cardiac death in young adults are, in descending order of frequency, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, coronary artery anomalies with an interarterial or intramural course, and ARVC. Often, sudden cardiac death is precipitated by ventricular tachycardia or fibrillation and may be prevented with an implantable cardioverter defibrillator (ICD). Risk stratification to determine the need for an ICD is challenging and involves imaging, particularly echocardiography and cardiac magnetic resonance (MR) imaging. Coronary artery anomalies, a diverse group of congenital disorders with a variable manifestation, may be depicted at coronary computed tomographic angiography or MR angiography. A thorough understanding of clinical risk stratification, imaging features, and complementary diagnostic tools for the evaluation of cardiac disorders that may lead to sudden cardiac death is essential to effectively use imaging to guide diagnosis and therapy.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.337125073">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.337125073">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig1a.jpeg" height="822" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Anomalous right coronary artery in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Reformatted oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) 3D SSFP cardiac MR image obtained with a free-breathing navigator-gated technique shows the right coronary artery (arrowhead) arising anteriorly from the left sinus of Valsalva <i>(L)</i>. <b>*</b> = pulmonary trunk, <i>N</i> = noncoronary sinus of Valsalva, <i>R</i> = right sinus of Valsalva, arrow = pulmonary valve. <b>(b)</b> Reformatted oblique MIP cardiac MR image shows the right coronary artery (arrowhead) coursing between the aortic root <i>(Ao)</i> and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i>, toward the right atrioventricular groove. <b>*</b> = pulmonary trunk, <i>RA</i> = right atrial appendage, <i>RPA</i> = right pulmonary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig1b.jpeg" height="822" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Anomalous right coronary artery in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Reformatted oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) 3D SSFP cardiac MR image obtained with a free-breathing navigator-gated technique shows the right coronary artery (arrowhead) arising anteriorly from the left sinus of Valsalva <i>(L)</i>. <b>*</b> = pulmonary trunk, <i>N</i> = noncoronary sinus of Valsalva, <i>R</i> = right sinus of Valsalva, arrow = pulmonary valve. <b>(b)</b> Reformatted oblique MIP cardiac MR image shows the right coronary artery (arrowhead) coursing between the aortic root <i>(Ao)</i> and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i>, toward the right atrioventricular groove. <b>*</b> = pulmonary trunk, <i>RA</i> = right atrial appendage, <i>RPA</i> = right pulmonary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig2a.jpeg" height="633" width="752" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Anomalous coronary artery found at coronary catheterization in a 62-year-old man with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique MIP CT image shows the left main (arrow) and right (arrowhead) coronary arteries arising as a common trunk from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i>. The left main coronary artery follows an interarterial course between the aorta and pulmonary artery (<b>*</b>). <i>L</i> = left sinus of Valsalva, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>N</i> = noncoronary sinus of Valsalva, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal MIP CT image shows the left main coronary artery (black arrow) passing between the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and the pulmonary artery (<b>*</b>) at the level of the pulmonary valve (white arrow). It is surrounded by fat. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig2b.jpeg" height="633" width="723" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Anomalous coronary artery found at coronary catheterization in a 62-year-old man with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique MIP CT image shows the left main (arrow) and right (arrowhead) coronary arteries arising as a common trunk from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i>. The left main coronary artery follows an interarterial course between the aorta and pulmonary artery (<b>*</b>). <i>L</i> = left sinus of Valsalva, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>N</i> = noncoronary sinus of Valsalva, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal MIP CT image shows the left main coronary artery (black arrow) passing between the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and the pulmonary artery (<b>*</b>) at the level of the pulmonary valve (white arrow). It is surrounded by fat. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig3a.jpeg" height="636" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Anomalous left main coronary artery seen at coronary CT angiography in a 17-year-old boy with syncope after running 1 mile at the gym. <b>(a)</b> Curved multiplanar reformation (MPR) CT image shows the left main coronary artery arising from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i> with an acute angle takeoff and proximal narrowing (arrow), findings indicative of an intramural course. <b>(b, c)</b> Orthogonal CT images obtained at the level of the anomalous artery show the classic slitlike orifice of the intramural portion (arrow) of the left main coronary artery. <b>(d)</b> Orthogonal CT image shows the anomalous artery, which reverts to a normal round appearance distally (arrowhead). (Image courtesy of Dr Maryam Ghadimi-Mahani, University of Michigan Department of Radiology, Division of Cardiothoracic Radiology.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig3b.jpeg" height="636" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Anomalous left main coronary artery seen at coronary CT angiography in a 17-year-old boy with syncope after running 1 mile at the gym. <b>(a)</b> Curved multiplanar reformation (MPR) CT image shows the left main coronary artery arising from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i> with an acute angle takeoff and proximal narrowing (arrow), findings indicative of an intramural course. <b>(b, c)</b> Orthogonal CT images obtained at the level of the anomalous artery show the classic slitlike orifice of the intramural portion (arrow) of the left main coronary artery. <b>(d)</b> Orthogonal CT image shows the anomalous artery, which reverts to a normal round appearance distally (arrowhead). (Image courtesy of Dr Maryam Ghadimi-Mahani, University of Michigan Department of Radiology, Division of Cardiothoracic Radiology.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig3c.jpeg" height="681" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Anomalous left main coronary artery seen at coronary CT angiography in a 17-year-old boy with syncope after running 1 mile at the gym. <b>(a)</b> Curved multiplanar reformation (MPR) CT image shows the left main coronary artery arising from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i> with an acute angle takeoff and proximal narrowing (arrow), findings indicative of an intramural course. <b>(b, c)</b> Orthogonal CT images obtained at the level of the anomalous artery show the classic slitlike orifice of the intramural portion (arrow) of the left main coronary artery. <b>(d)</b> Orthogonal CT image shows the anomalous artery, which reverts to a normal round appearance distally (arrowhead). (Image courtesy of Dr Maryam Ghadimi-Mahani, University of Michigan Department of Radiology, Division of Cardiothoracic Radiology.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig3d.jpeg" height="681" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span> Anomalous left main coronary artery seen at coronary CT angiography in a 17-year-old boy with syncope after running 1 mile at the gym. <b>(a)</b> Curved multiplanar reformation (MPR) CT image shows the left main coronary artery arising from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i> with an acute angle takeoff and proximal narrowing (arrow), findings indicative of an intramural course. <b>(b, c)</b> Orthogonal CT images obtained at the level of the anomalous artery show the classic slitlike orifice of the intramural portion (arrow) of the left main coronary artery. <b>(d)</b> Orthogonal CT image shows the anomalous artery, which reverts to a normal round appearance distally (arrowhead). (Image courtesy of Dr Maryam Ghadimi-Mahani, University of Michigan Department of Radiology, Division of Cardiothoracic Radiology.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig4a.jpeg" height="740" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Anomalous left main coronary artery seen at coronary CT angiography in a 58-year-old woman with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique MIP CT image shows a separate origin of the left main coronary artery from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i>. The left main coronary artery follows a transseptal course (arrow). Arrowhead = right coronary artery. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the origin of the left main coronary artery (arrow) from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i>. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle, <b>*</b> = pulmonary artery. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal CT images show the anomalous artery coursing in the upper aspect of the ventricular septum (black arrow) and giving rise to a septal perforator (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>*</b> = pulmonary artery, white arrow in <b>c</b> = pulmonary valve, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the anomalous left main coronary artery (arrow) ascending to the epicardial surface, where it is surrounded by epicardial fat. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig4b.jpeg" height="742" width="729" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Anomalous left main coronary artery seen at coronary CT angiography in a 58-year-old woman with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique MIP CT image shows a separate origin of the left main coronary artery from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i>. The left main coronary artery follows a transseptal course (arrow). Arrowhead = right coronary artery. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the origin of the left main coronary artery (arrow) from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i>. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle, <b>*</b> = pulmonary artery. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal CT images show the anomalous artery coursing in the upper aspect of the ventricular septum (black arrow) and giving rise to a septal perforator (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>*</b> = pulmonary artery, white arrow in <b>c</b> = pulmonary valve, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the anomalous left main coronary artery (arrow) ascending to the epicardial surface, where it is surrounded by epicardial fat. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig4c.jpeg" height="742" width="746" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> Anomalous left main coronary artery seen at coronary CT angiography in a 58-year-old woman with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique MIP CT image shows a separate origin of the left main coronary artery from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i>. The left main coronary artery follows a transseptal course (arrow). Arrowhead = right coronary artery. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the origin of the left main coronary artery (arrow) from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i>. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle, <b>*</b> = pulmonary artery. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal CT images show the anomalous artery coursing in the upper aspect of the ventricular septum (black arrow) and giving rise to a septal perforator (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>*</b> = pulmonary artery, white arrow in <b>c</b> = pulmonary valve, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the anomalous left main coronary artery (arrow) ascending to the epicardial surface, where it is surrounded by epicardial fat. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig4d.jpeg" height="694" width="751" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span> Anomalous left main coronary artery seen at coronary CT angiography in a 58-year-old woman with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique MIP CT image shows a separate origin of the left main coronary artery from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i>. The left main coronary artery follows a transseptal course (arrow). Arrowhead = right coronary artery. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the origin of the left main coronary artery (arrow) from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i>. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle, <b>*</b> = pulmonary artery. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal CT images show the anomalous artery coursing in the upper aspect of the ventricular septum (black arrow) and giving rise to a septal perforator (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>*</b> = pulmonary artery, white arrow in <b>c</b> = pulmonary valve, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the anomalous left main coronary artery (arrow) ascending to the epicardial surface, where it is surrounded by epicardial fat. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig4e.jpeg" height="694" width="724" aria-labelledby="fig4e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4e</span> Anomalous left main coronary artery seen at coronary CT angiography in a 58-year-old woman with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique MIP CT image shows a separate origin of the left main coronary artery from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i>. The left main coronary artery follows a transseptal course (arrow). Arrowhead = right coronary artery. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the origin of the left main coronary artery (arrow) from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(R)</i>. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle, <b>*</b> = pulmonary artery. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal CT images show the anomalous artery coursing in the upper aspect of the ventricular septum (black arrow) and giving rise to a septal perforator (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>*</b> = pulmonary artery, white arrow in <b>c</b> = pulmonary valve, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the anomalous left main coronary artery (arrow) ascending to the epicardial surface, where it is surrounded by epicardial fat. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig4e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig5a.jpeg" height="760" width="746" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image, obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT in a 17-year-old boy with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy found at family screening, shows marked asymmetric septal hypertrophy with a ratio of ventricular septal thickness (27 mm, arrow) to inferiolateral wall thickness (9 mm, arrowhead) of 3:1. Note that the hypertrophied septum encroaches on the left ventricular lumen, causing mild narrowing of the LVOT (<b>*</b>). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image, obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT in a 41-year-old man with abnormal findings at EKG, shows apical hypertrophy of the left ventricle (white arrows), with sparing of the ventricular base and a widely patent LVOT (<b>*</b>).<i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig5b.jpeg" height="760" width="729" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image, obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT in a 17-year-old boy with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy found at family screening, shows marked asymmetric septal hypertrophy with a ratio of ventricular septal thickness (27 mm, arrow) to inferiolateral wall thickness (9 mm, arrowhead) of 3:1. Note that the hypertrophied septum encroaches on the left ventricular lumen, causing mild narrowing of the LVOT (<b>*</b>). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image, obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT in a 41-year-old man with abnormal findings at EKG, shows apical hypertrophy of the left ventricle (white arrows), with sparing of the ventricular base and a widely patent LVOT (<b>*</b>).<i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig6.jpeg" height="764" width="736" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT in a healthy 35-year-old woman with normal, homogeneous left ventricular myocardial thickness (arrow) shows that ventricular septal thickness is 8 mm and equals that of the inferolateral wall (white arrowhead), for a ratio of 1:1. Note the normal tapering of myocardial thickness at the apex of the left ventricle (black arrowhead) and that the LVOT (<b>*</b>) is patent. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig7a.jpeg" height="764" width="739" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Apical to midventricular hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and apical aneurysm in a 58-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Horizontal long-axis 2D SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole shows mildly asymmetric left ventricular hypertrophy that is most severe at the midventricular level (<b>*</b>). Thinning of the left ventricular apex is also seen. <b>(b)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end systole shows no contraction with bulging of the left ventricular apex (arrowhead) and obliteration of the midventricular cavity. <b>(c)</b> Late contrast-enhanced MR image shows enhancement of the left ventricular apex. Left ventricular apical aneurysm is a known complication of midventricular and apical hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig7b.jpeg" height="766" width="739" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Apical to midventricular hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and apical aneurysm in a 58-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Horizontal long-axis 2D SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole shows mildly asymmetric left ventricular hypertrophy that is most severe at the midventricular level (<b>*</b>). Thinning of the left ventricular apex is also seen. <b>(b)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end systole shows no contraction with bulging of the left ventricular apex (arrowhead) and obliteration of the midventricular cavity. <b>(c)</b> Late contrast-enhanced MR image shows enhancement of the left ventricular apex. Left ventricular apical aneurysm is a known complication of midventricular and apical hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig7c.jpeg" height="766" width="736" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Apical to midventricular hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and apical aneurysm in a 58-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Horizontal long-axis 2D SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole shows mildly asymmetric left ventricular hypertrophy that is most severe at the midventricular level (<b>*</b>). Thinning of the left ventricular apex is also seen. <b>(b)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end systole shows no contraction with bulging of the left ventricular apex (arrowhead) and obliteration of the midventricular cavity. <b>(c)</b> Late contrast-enhanced MR image shows enhancement of the left ventricular apex. Left ventricular apical aneurysm is a known complication of midventricular and apical hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig8.jpeg" height="713" width="763" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in a 15-year-old boy. Short-axis 2D SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in end diastole shows segmental hypertrophy (<b>*</b>) that is restricted to the anterior septum, simulating a mass. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig9.jpeg" height="713" width="712" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in a 20-year-old woman. Horizontal long-axis 2D SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in end diastole shows asymmetric septal hypertrophy (<b>*</b>) and hypertrophy in the right ventricular free wall (arrow). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig10a.jpeg" height="679" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> SAM, dynamic LVOT obstruction, and mitral valve regurgitation in a 53-year-old man with long-standing known hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in early systole shows a closed mitral valve, the coaptation point of the anterior and posterior leaflet (white arrow), and the subtle structure of a chordae tendinae (black arrow). The LVOT is not substantially narrowed (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in late systole shows substantial narrowing of the LVOT. The tip of the anterior mitral valve leaflet (white arrow) is bent toward, and almost abuts, the septum, and a flow jet (arrowhead) emanates from the anterior mitral valve leaflet, a finding that indicates acceleration of flow in the LVOT. The chordae tendinae are also seen in close proximity to the septum (black arrow). <b>(c)</b> Apical four-chamber 2D echocardiogram shows the mitral valve leaflet (white arrow) bent toward the thickened septum <i>(S)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig10b.jpeg" height="679" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> SAM, dynamic LVOT obstruction, and mitral valve regurgitation in a 53-year-old man with long-standing known hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in early systole shows a closed mitral valve, the coaptation point of the anterior and posterior leaflet (white arrow), and the subtle structure of a chordae tendinae (black arrow). The LVOT is not substantially narrowed (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in late systole shows substantial narrowing of the LVOT. The tip of the anterior mitral valve leaflet (white arrow) is bent toward, and almost abuts, the septum, and a flow jet (arrowhead) emanates from the anterior mitral valve leaflet, a finding that indicates acceleration of flow in the LVOT. The chordae tendinae are also seen in close proximity to the septum (black arrow). <b>(c)</b> Apical four-chamber 2D echocardiogram shows the mitral valve leaflet (white arrow) bent toward the thickened septum <i>(S)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig10c.jpeg" height="583" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> SAM, dynamic LVOT obstruction, and mitral valve regurgitation in a 53-year-old man with long-standing known hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in early systole shows a closed mitral valve, the coaptation point of the anterior and posterior leaflet (white arrow), and the subtle structure of a chordae tendinae (black arrow). The LVOT is not substantially narrowed (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in late systole shows substantial narrowing of the LVOT. The tip of the anterior mitral valve leaflet (white arrow) is bent toward, and almost abuts, the septum, and a flow jet (arrowhead) emanates from the anterior mitral valve leaflet, a finding that indicates acceleration of flow in the LVOT. The chordae tendinae are also seen in close proximity to the septum (black arrow). <b>(c)</b> Apical four-chamber 2D echocardiogram shows the mitral valve leaflet (white arrow) bent toward the thickened septum <i>(S)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig11a.jpeg" height="738" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in a 57-year-old man with a 2-year history of exertional dyspnea and chest discomfort who underwent ICD placement for primary prevention of sudden cardiac death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis 2D SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole shows asymmetric septal hypertrophy with a maximal thickness of 31.9 mm encroaching on the ventricular lumen. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows a patchy nodular area of enhancement in the hypertrophied septum (arrow) that does not correspond to a coronary artery territory and, therefore, is distinctly different from an infarct scar. <b>(c)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in end systole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows marked asymmetric septal hypertrophy encroaching on the left ventricular lumen and causing narrowing of the mid ventricle and LVOT (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Posteroanterior radiograph shows an ICD in the wall of the left side of the chest.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig11b.jpeg" height="738" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in a 57-year-old man with a 2-year history of exertional dyspnea and chest discomfort who underwent ICD placement for primary prevention of sudden cardiac death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis 2D SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole shows asymmetric septal hypertrophy with a maximal thickness of 31.9 mm encroaching on the ventricular lumen. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows a patchy nodular area of enhancement in the hypertrophied septum (arrow) that does not correspond to a coronary artery territory and, therefore, is distinctly different from an infarct scar. <b>(c)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in end systole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows marked asymmetric septal hypertrophy encroaching on the left ventricular lumen and causing narrowing of the mid ventricle and LVOT (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Posteroanterior radiograph shows an ICD in the wall of the left side of the chest.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig11c.jpeg" height="738" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in a 57-year-old man with a 2-year history of exertional dyspnea and chest discomfort who underwent ICD placement for primary prevention of sudden cardiac death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis 2D SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole shows asymmetric septal hypertrophy with a maximal thickness of 31.9 mm encroaching on the ventricular lumen. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows a patchy nodular area of enhancement in the hypertrophied septum (arrow) that does not correspond to a coronary artery territory and, therefore, is distinctly different from an infarct scar. <b>(c)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in end systole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows marked asymmetric septal hypertrophy encroaching on the left ventricular lumen and causing narrowing of the mid ventricle and LVOT (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Posteroanterior radiograph shows an ICD in the wall of the left side of the chest.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig11d.jpeg" height="738" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span> Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in a 57-year-old man with a 2-year history of exertional dyspnea and chest discomfort who underwent ICD placement for primary prevention of sudden cardiac death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis 2D SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole shows asymmetric septal hypertrophy with a maximal thickness of 31.9 mm encroaching on the ventricular lumen. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows a patchy nodular area of enhancement in the hypertrophied septum (arrow) that does not correspond to a coronary artery territory and, therefore, is distinctly different from an infarct scar. <b>(c)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in end systole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows marked asymmetric septal hypertrophy encroaching on the left ventricular lumen and causing narrowing of the mid ventricle and LVOT (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Posteroanterior radiograph shows an ICD in the wall of the left side of the chest.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig12a.jpeg" height="756" width="741" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Three differential diagnoses for hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Athlete’s heart found at screening in a 16-year-old boy. Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows mild eccentric left ventricular hypertrophy, with a maximal thickness of 13 mm at the inferolateral wall. The indexed left ventricular end-diastolic volume is 99 mL/m<sup>2</sup>. The ratio of end-diastolic wall thickness to end-diastolic left ventricular volume index is 0.13 mm × m<sup>2</sup> × mL<sup>−1</sup>. <b>(b)</b> Bicuspid aortic valve and moderate aortic stenosis in a 60-year-old man. Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows concentric left ventricular hypertrophy, with a maximal thickness of 21 mm at the base of the anteroseptal wall, and a flow jet emanating from the aortic valve, which is stenotic. <b>(c)</b> Long-standing systemic hypertension in a 59-year-old man. Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows mild asymmetric left ventricular hypertrophy with a maximal thickness of 17 mm at the anteroseptal wall and dilatation of the left atrium. The left ventricle is normal in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig12b.jpeg" height="629" width="816" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Three differential diagnoses for hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Athlete’s heart found at screening in a 16-year-old boy. Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows mild eccentric left ventricular hypertrophy, with a maximal thickness of 13 mm at the inferolateral wall. The indexed left ventricular end-diastolic volume is 99 mL/m<sup>2</sup>. The ratio of end-diastolic wall thickness to end-diastolic left ventricular volume index is 0.13 mm × m<sup>2</sup> × mL<sup>−1</sup>. <b>(b)</b> Bicuspid aortic valve and moderate aortic stenosis in a 60-year-old man. Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows concentric left ventricular hypertrophy, with a maximal thickness of 21 mm at the base of the anteroseptal wall, and a flow jet emanating from the aortic valve, which is stenotic. <b>(c)</b> Long-standing systemic hypertension in a 59-year-old man. Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows mild asymmetric left ventricular hypertrophy with a maximal thickness of 17 mm at the anteroseptal wall and dilatation of the left atrium. The left ventricle is normal in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig12c.jpeg" height="628" width="858" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Three differential diagnoses for hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Athlete’s heart found at screening in a 16-year-old boy. Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows mild eccentric left ventricular hypertrophy, with a maximal thickness of 13 mm at the inferolateral wall. The indexed left ventricular end-diastolic volume is 99 mL/m<sup>2</sup>. The ratio of end-diastolic wall thickness to end-diastolic left ventricular volume index is 0.13 mm × m<sup>2</sup> × mL<sup>−1</sup>. <b>(b)</b> Bicuspid aortic valve and moderate aortic stenosis in a 60-year-old man. Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows concentric left ventricular hypertrophy, with a maximal thickness of 21 mm at the base of the anteroseptal wall, and a flow jet emanating from the aortic valve, which is stenotic. <b>(c)</b> Long-standing systemic hypertension in a 59-year-old man. Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows mild asymmetric left ventricular hypertrophy with a maximal thickness of 17 mm at the anteroseptal wall and dilatation of the left atrium. The left ventricle is normal in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig13.jpeg" height="756" width="734" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Restrictive cardiomyopathy secondary to amyloidosis (confirmed at endomyocardial biopsy) in a 60-year-old woman with low voltage at ECG. Short-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows diffuse subendocardial enhancement in both the left and right ventricular myocardium (arrows) and pericardial effusion (arrowheads). <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig14a.jpeg" height="706" width="759" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Danon disease in an 18-year-old man with left ventricular hypertrophy and a Wolff-Parkinson-White pattern at preoperative ECG. <b>(a)</b> Parasternal long-axis echocardiogram shows concentric left ventricular hypertrophy. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <b>*</b> = LVOT. <b>(b, c)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR images obtained in the long-axis plane of the LVOT (<b>*</b>) in end diastole <b>(b)</b> and end systole <b>(c)</b> show concentric left ventricular hypertrophy (anterior septal wall thickness, 35 mm; inferolateral wall thickness, 30 mm) and a narrow left ventricular lumen. The left ventricular ejection fraction is 48%, and no SAM is present. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows extensive enhancement in the midwall (arrows), predominantly in the lateral, anterior, and inferior left ventricular wall. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig14b.jpeg" height="706" width="716" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Danon disease in an 18-year-old man with left ventricular hypertrophy and a Wolff-Parkinson-White pattern at preoperative ECG. <b>(a)</b> Parasternal long-axis echocardiogram shows concentric left ventricular hypertrophy. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <b>*</b> = LVOT. <b>(b, c)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR images obtained in the long-axis plane of the LVOT (<b>*</b>) in end diastole <b>(b)</b> and end systole <b>(c)</b> show concentric left ventricular hypertrophy (anterior septal wall thickness, 35 mm; inferolateral wall thickness, 30 mm) and a narrow left ventricular lumen. The left ventricular ejection fraction is 48%, and no SAM is present. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows extensive enhancement in the midwall (arrows), predominantly in the lateral, anterior, and inferior left ventricular wall. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig14c.jpeg" height="711" width="735" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span> Danon disease in an 18-year-old man with left ventricular hypertrophy and a Wolff-Parkinson-White pattern at preoperative ECG. <b>(a)</b> Parasternal long-axis echocardiogram shows concentric left ventricular hypertrophy. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <b>*</b> = LVOT. <b>(b, c)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR images obtained in the long-axis plane of the LVOT (<b>*</b>) in end diastole <b>(b)</b> and end systole <b>(c)</b> show concentric left ventricular hypertrophy (anterior septal wall thickness, 35 mm; inferolateral wall thickness, 30 mm) and a narrow left ventricular lumen. The left ventricular ejection fraction is 48%, and no SAM is present. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows extensive enhancement in the midwall (arrows), predominantly in the lateral, anterior, and inferior left ventricular wall. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig14d.jpeg" height="711" width="739" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span> Danon disease in an 18-year-old man with left ventricular hypertrophy and a Wolff-Parkinson-White pattern at preoperative ECG. <b>(a)</b> Parasternal long-axis echocardiogram shows concentric left ventricular hypertrophy. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <b>*</b> = LVOT. <b>(b, c)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR images obtained in the long-axis plane of the LVOT (<b>*</b>) in end diastole <b>(b)</b> and end systole <b>(c)</b> show concentric left ventricular hypertrophy (anterior septal wall thickness, 35 mm; inferolateral wall thickness, 30 mm) and a narrow left ventricular lumen. The left ventricular ejection fraction is 48%, and no SAM is present. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows extensive enhancement in the midwall (arrows), predominantly in the lateral, anterior, and inferior left ventricular wall. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig15a.jpeg" height="541" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Fabry disease in a 43-year-old woman with a family history of the condition. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows asymmetric hypertrophy of the basal septum, with a maximal thickness of 24.2 mm. <b>(b)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end systole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows narrowing of the LVOT, a focal area of akinesis (arrowhead), and enlargement of the left atrium (diameter, 48.1 mm in the anteroposterior direction). <b>(c)</b> Late contrast-enhanced MR image shows an enhancing scar that corresponds to the area of akinesis (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig15b.jpeg" height="638" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Fabry disease in a 43-year-old woman with a family history of the condition. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows asymmetric hypertrophy of the basal septum, with a maximal thickness of 24.2 mm. <b>(b)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end systole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows narrowing of the LVOT, a focal area of akinesis (arrowhead), and enlargement of the left atrium (diameter, 48.1 mm in the anteroposterior direction). <b>(c)</b> Late contrast-enhanced MR image shows an enhancing scar that corresponds to the area of akinesis (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig15c.jpeg" height="638" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span> Fabry disease in a 43-year-old woman with a family history of the condition. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows asymmetric hypertrophy of the basal septum, with a maximal thickness of 24.2 mm. <b>(b)</b> Two-dimensional SSFP MR image obtained in end systole in the long-axis plane of the LVOT shows narrowing of the LVOT, a focal area of akinesis (arrowhead), and enlargement of the left atrium (diameter, 48.1 mm in the anteroposterior direction). <b>(c)</b> Late contrast-enhanced MR image shows an enhancing scar that corresponds to the area of akinesis (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig16a.jpeg" height="664" width="725" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> ARVC in a 17-year-old boy who experienced sudden cardiac death from sustained ventricular tachycardia during a soccer match and was revived with on-site defibrillation. <b>(a</b>–<b>d)</b> Parasternal long-axis 2D echocardiograms <b>(a, b)</b> and short-axis 2D SSFP cardiac MR images <b>(c, d)</b> obtained in end diastole <b>(a, c)</b> and end systole <b>(b, d)</b> show a dilated right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and regional dyskinesis at the RVOT (arrow). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(e)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows dilatation of the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and bulging of the RVOT (arrowhead). An ICD (arrows) was placed for secondary prevention of sudden cardiac death. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig16b.jpeg" height="664" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> ARVC in a 17-year-old boy who experienced sudden cardiac death from sustained ventricular tachycardia during a soccer match and was revived with on-site defibrillation. <b>(a</b>–<b>d)</b> Parasternal long-axis 2D echocardiograms <b>(a, b)</b> and short-axis 2D SSFP cardiac MR images <b>(c, d)</b> obtained in end diastole <b>(a, c)</b> and end systole <b>(b, d)</b> show a dilated right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and regional dyskinesis at the RVOT (arrow). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(e)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows dilatation of the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and bulging of the RVOT (arrowhead). An ICD (arrows) was placed for secondary prevention of sudden cardiac death. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig16c.jpeg" height="680" width="774" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> ARVC in a 17-year-old boy who experienced sudden cardiac death from sustained ventricular tachycardia during a soccer match and was revived with on-site defibrillation. <b>(a</b>–<b>d)</b> Parasternal long-axis 2D echocardiograms <b>(a, b)</b> and short-axis 2D SSFP cardiac MR images <b>(c, d)</b> obtained in end diastole <b>(a, c)</b> and end systole <b>(b, d)</b> show a dilated right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and regional dyskinesis at the RVOT (arrow). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(e)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows dilatation of the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and bulging of the RVOT (arrowhead). An ICD (arrows) was placed for secondary prevention of sudden cardiac death. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig16d.jpeg" height="680" width="701" aria-labelledby="fig16d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16d</span> ARVC in a 17-year-old boy who experienced sudden cardiac death from sustained ventricular tachycardia during a soccer match and was revived with on-site defibrillation. <b>(a</b>–<b>d)</b> Parasternal long-axis 2D echocardiograms <b>(a, b)</b> and short-axis 2D SSFP cardiac MR images <b>(c, d)</b> obtained in end diastole <b>(a, c)</b> and end systole <b>(b, d)</b> show a dilated right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and regional dyskinesis at the RVOT (arrow). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(e)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows dilatation of the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and bulging of the RVOT (arrowhead). An ICD (arrows) was placed for secondary prevention of sudden cardiac death. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig16d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig16e.jpeg" height="673" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig16e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16e</span> ARVC in a 17-year-old boy who experienced sudden cardiac death from sustained ventricular tachycardia during a soccer match and was revived with on-site defibrillation. <b>(a</b>–<b>d)</b> Parasternal long-axis 2D echocardiograms <b>(a, b)</b> and short-axis 2D SSFP cardiac MR images <b>(c, d)</b> obtained in end diastole <b>(a, c)</b> and end systole <b>(b, d)</b> show a dilated right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and regional dyskinesis at the RVOT (arrow). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(e)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows dilatation of the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and bulging of the RVOT (arrowhead). An ICD (arrows) was placed for secondary prevention of sudden cardiac death. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig16e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig17.jpeg" height="641" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Wide complex ventricular tachycardia and cardiac sarcoidosis confirmed at endomyocardial biopsy in a 34-year-old woman. Short-axis late contrast-enhanced cardiac MR image shows enhancement of the subepicardial left ventricle (arrowhead), the ventricular septum (black arrow), and the RVOT (white arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig18a.jpeg" height="641" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Partial anomalous pulmonary venous return causing a left-to-right shunt in a 41-year-old man who presented with arrhythmia. Right ventricular dilatation was incidentally found at echocardiography and was suspicious for ARVC. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis 2D SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole shows dilatation of the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i>. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b, c)</b> MIP <b>(b)</b> and axial contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> CT images show partial anomalous return of a large left superior pulmonary vein (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) into a vertical vein (arrow in <b>c</b>) that courses to the left of the aortic arch.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig18b.jpeg" height="737" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Partial anomalous pulmonary venous return causing a left-to-right shunt in a 41-year-old man who presented with arrhythmia. Right ventricular dilatation was incidentally found at echocardiography and was suspicious for ARVC. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis 2D SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole shows dilatation of the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i>. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b, c)</b> MIP <b>(b)</b> and axial contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> CT images show partial anomalous return of a large left superior pulmonary vein (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) into a vertical vein (arrow in <b>c</b>) that courses to the left of the aortic arch.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig18c.jpeg" height="737" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span> Partial anomalous pulmonary venous return causing a left-to-right shunt in a 41-year-old man who presented with arrhythmia. Right ventricular dilatation was incidentally found at echocardiography and was suspicious for ARVC. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis 2D SSFP MR image obtained in end diastole shows dilatation of the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i>. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b, c)</b> MIP <b>(b)</b> and axial contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> CT images show partial anomalous return of a large left superior pulmonary vein (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) into a vertical vein (arrow in <b>c</b>) that courses to the left of the aortic arch.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig19a.jpeg" height="686" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 36-year-old male soccer player with fatigue and a 3–5-day history of burning epigastric pain associated with nausea, vomiting, and early satiety. <b>(a)</b> Long-axis echocardiogram shows dilatation of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> and an apical thrombus (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Horizontal long-axis 2D SSFP MR images obtained in end diastole <b>(b)</b> and end systole <b>(c)</b> show cardiomegaly and severe global hypokinesis of the left <i>(LV)</i> and right <i>(RV)</i> ventricles. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(d)</b> Horizontal long-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows an apical thrombus (arrow) in the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> and midwall enhancement in the lateral left ventricular wall (white arrowhead) and the interventricular septum (black arrowhead). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig19b.jpeg" height="686" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 36-year-old male soccer player with fatigue and a 3–5-day history of burning epigastric pain associated with nausea, vomiting, and early satiety. <b>(a)</b> Long-axis echocardiogram shows dilatation of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> and an apical thrombus (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Horizontal long-axis 2D SSFP MR images obtained in end diastole <b>(b)</b> and end systole <b>(c)</b> show cardiomegaly and severe global hypokinesis of the left <i>(LV)</i> and right <i>(RV)</i> ventricles. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(d)</b> Horizontal long-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows an apical thrombus (arrow) in the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> and midwall enhancement in the lateral left ventricular wall (white arrowhead) and the interventricular septum (black arrowhead). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig19c.jpeg" height="681" width="733" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span> Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 36-year-old male soccer player with fatigue and a 3–5-day history of burning epigastric pain associated with nausea, vomiting, and early satiety. <b>(a)</b> Long-axis echocardiogram shows dilatation of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> and an apical thrombus (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Horizontal long-axis 2D SSFP MR images obtained in end diastole <b>(b)</b> and end systole <b>(c)</b> show cardiomegaly and severe global hypokinesis of the left <i>(LV)</i> and right <i>(RV)</i> ventricles. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(d)</b> Horizontal long-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows an apical thrombus (arrow) in the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> and midwall enhancement in the lateral left ventricular wall (white arrowhead) and the interventricular septum (black arrowhead). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig19d.jpeg" height="682" width="742" aria-labelledby="fig19d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19d</span> Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 36-year-old male soccer player with fatigue and a 3–5-day history of burning epigastric pain associated with nausea, vomiting, and early satiety. <b>(a)</b> Long-axis echocardiogram shows dilatation of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> and an apical thrombus (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Horizontal long-axis 2D SSFP MR images obtained in end diastole <b>(b)</b> and end systole <b>(c)</b> show cardiomegaly and severe global hypokinesis of the left <i>(LV)</i> and right <i>(RV)</i> ventricles. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(d)</b> Horizontal long-axis late contrast-enhanced MR image shows an apical thrombus (arrow) in the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> and midwall enhancement in the lateral left ventricular wall (white arrowhead) and the interventricular septum (black arrowhead). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig19d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig20a.jpeg" height="689" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> Myocarditis associated with sudden cardiac death in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Subacute heart failure in a 60-year-old woman with suspected giant cell myocarditis, which was confirmed at autopsy. Late contrast-enhanced cardiac MR image shows enhancement along the right ventricular side of the ventricular septum (arrow) and along the right ventricular free wall (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Recurrent tachycardia in a 32-year-old woman with a history of sepsis and myocarditis. Late contrast-enhanced cardiac MR image (four-chamber view) shows midwall enhancement in the ventricular septum (arrow) and, to a lesser extent, the mid lateral wall of the left ventricle (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig20b.jpeg" height="689" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> Myocarditis associated with sudden cardiac death in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Subacute heart failure in a 60-year-old woman with suspected giant cell myocarditis, which was confirmed at autopsy. Late contrast-enhanced cardiac MR image shows enhancement along the right ventricular side of the ventricular septum (arrow) and along the right ventricular free wall (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Recurrent tachycardia in a 32-year-old woman with a history of sepsis and myocarditis. Late contrast-enhanced cardiac MR image (four-chamber view) shows midwall enhancement in the ventricular septum (arrow) and, to a lesser extent, the mid lateral wall of the left ventricle (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig21a.jpeg" height="671" width="839" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span> Noncompaction cardiomyopathy in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 60-year-old man with new-onset congestive heart failure. Short-axis echocardiogram obtained in systole at the level of the left ventricle shows a two-layered myocardium with a noncompacted (red line) and compacted (green line) layer along the lateral, inferior, and anterior walls and a maximal end-systolic NC:C ratio of more than 2. <b>(b)</b> Symptoms of New York Heart Association Class III heart failure and severely reduced (35% or less) left ventricular ejection fraction in a 35-year-old woman. Short-axis 2D SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in end diastole shows thickening of the noncompacted layer of the left ventricular myocardium, with an NC:C ratio of 2.9. The patient underwent subsequent ICD placement for primary prevention of sudden cardiac death.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337125073/asset/images/large/rg.337125073.fig21b.jpeg" height="670" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span> Noncompaction cardiomyopathy in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 60-year-old man with new-onset congestive heart failure. Short-axis echocardiogram obtained in systole at the level of the left ventricle shows a two-layered myocardium with a noncompacted (red line) and compacted (green line) layer along the lateral, inferior, and anterior walls and a maximal end-systolic NC:C ratio of more than 2. <b>(b)</b> Symptoms of New York Heart Association Class III heart failure and severely reduced (35% or less) left ventricular ejection fraction in a 35-year-old woman. Short-axis 2D SSFP cardiac MR image obtained in end diastole shows thickening of the noncompacted layer of the left ventricular myocardium, with an NC:C ratio of 2.9. The patient underwent subsequent ICD placement for primary prevention of sudden cardiac death.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337125073&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Zipes DP, Camm AJ, Borggrefe M, et al. ACC/AHA/ESC 2006 Guidelines for Management of Patients With Ventricular Arrhythmias and the Prevention of Sudden Cardiac Death: a report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force and the European Society of Cardiology Committee for Practice Guidelines (writing committee to develop Guidelines for Management of Patients With Ventricular Arrhythmias and the Prevention of Sudden Cardiac Death): developed in collaboration with the European Heart Rhythm Association and the Heart Rhythm Society. <em>Circulation</em> 2006;114(10):e385–e484.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.106.178233">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16935995/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=ACC%2FAHA%2FESC+2006+Guidelines+for+Management+of+Patients+With+Ventricul